I'd like to suggest adding a Math method, perhaps called `_.bounds`, to find both the minimum and maximum value of an array **in one pass**. The method would return an array of the form `[minValue, maxValue]`.

Lodash includes methods for finding the minimum and maximum value in an array independently, but not both at the same time, in one pass. What I'm after is a more efficient and convenient version of:

```js
const bounds = [_.min(arr), _.max(arr)];
```

In my case, I would use this method to compute the **domain** of a dataset, which I need to create a **color scale** for data visualization purposes (with [d3-scale](https://github.com/d3/d3-scale)). I'm working with very large datasets, in the order of magnitude of 1 million points, so looping through them in a single pass instead of two is a significant optimisation.

Here is a basic vanilla ES5 implementation:

```js
function bounds(array) {
  return array.reduce(
    ([min, max], item) => [Math.min(item, min), Math.max(item, max)],
    [Infinity, -Infinity]
  );
}
```

It's worth noting that a few libraries already exist for this purpose, notably [array-bounds](https://github.com/dy/array-bounds), which additionally allows computing the bounds of a multi-dimensional array.

